  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions worldwide. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions, to make it appear legitimate.\n\nLaws against money laundering are in place to combat organized crime, terrorism, corruption, and other illegal activities that generate illicit funds. These laws require financial institutions and other businesses to implement measures to detect and report suspicious transactions. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines and lengthy prison sentences.\n\nIn China, for example, the Anti-Money Laundering Law (\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u53cd\u6d17\u94b1\u6cd5) was enacted to prevent and combat money laundering activities, and it imposes strict obligations on financial institutions to monitor and report suspicious transactions. The government actively cooperates with international efforts to combat money laundering through organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).",
